WEBVTT

00:00.640 --> 00:03.920
One of the greatest illusions in life is continuity.

00:05.200 --> 00:10.880
66 million years ago, the continuity of the dinosaurs had been going on for around

00:10.880 --> 00:17.040
165 million years already, and it didn't seem this would change anytime soon.

00:17.040 --> 00:21.760
The world was warm and pleasant, and most of the land was covered with lush forests

00:21.760 --> 00:27.760
and an incredible diversity of trees, flowers, ferns, and trillions of critters.

00:28.480 --> 00:34.320
Dinosaurs were ubiquitous and had diversified into hundreds of species of all shapes and sizes.

00:35.280 --> 00:41.600
Titanosaurs, large gentle giants, shared the world with famous beasts like Tyrannosaurus rex

00:41.600 --> 00:46.800
or Edmontosaurus. Pectinodon hunted in the undergrowth,

00:46.800 --> 00:50.320
while Edmontosaurus wandered coastlines and swamps.

00:51.280 --> 00:56.160
An ancient paradise, a world of plenty, full of life.

00:56.160 --> 01:03.280
66 million years ago, maybe on a Tuesday afternoon, life was the same as it had been

01:03.280 --> 01:08.480
the day before, or a thousand years before, or pretty much a million years before.

01:08.480 --> 01:15.360
Things were good for our feathered dinosaur buddies, until a tiny, tiny detail in the sky changed.

01:15.360 --> 01:29.600
If there were dinosaurs watching the stars, one night they may have noticed the appearance

01:29.600 --> 01:35.280
of a new star, a tiny dot that for many weeks slowly became bigger and brighter.

01:36.240 --> 01:41.200
Until one fateful day, it looked like another, small moon in the night sky.

01:42.000 --> 01:46.160
And then, it faded from sight as it dipped into Earth's shadow.

01:46.720 --> 01:53.360
For a few more hours, the illusion of continuity was upheld, until it was not anymore.

01:54.080 --> 02:00.160
In the morning, the object suddenly appears again, now almost as large as the sun in the sky and

02:00.160 --> 02:04.400
growing every moment, heading for the coast near the Yucatan Peninsula.

02:05.040 --> 02:08.800
It takes the asteroid only seconds to pass through the thin layer between

02:08.800 --> 02:14.080
space and the ground to make contact, as it enters the atmosphere at almost

02:14.080 --> 02:18.160
60 times the speed of sound. Let's stop time.

02:18.880 --> 02:26.320
Here, we see the unnamed asteroid about to commit specieside. Larger than Mount Everest,

02:26.320 --> 02:30.880
it reaches from the ocean high into the atmosphere, higher than passenger planes

02:30.880 --> 02:35.600
would fly millions of years later. At this moment, the world was one way.

02:36.160 --> 02:39.520
In a fraction of a second, it would be fundamentally different.

02:40.320 --> 02:44.160
Let's make the transition. As the asteroid hits the shallow

02:44.160 --> 02:49.200
ocean and the bedrock below, the energy of billions of nuclear weapons is released all

02:49.200 --> 02:55.520
at once as the asteroid vaporizes. A flash of light illuminates the sky

02:55.520 --> 02:59.280
as an eerie bright white sphere grows over the Gulf of Mexico.

03:00.000 --> 03:05.040
Bedrock melts into seething hot plasma at tens of thousands of degrees Celsius.

03:06.000 --> 03:11.200
The thermal radiation from the explosion travels at the speed of light and immediately burns

03:11.200 --> 03:16.640
everything within a radius of about 1,500 kilometers, while the energy from the impact

03:16.640 --> 03:22.960
pushes so hard against Earth's crust that it loses all strength and flows away from the impact site

03:22.960 --> 03:28.400
like a liquid, creating a hole 25 kilometers deep and 100 kilometers wide.

03:29.280 --> 03:34.000
The ocean is pushed back for hundreds of kilometers, like when a kid jumps into a puddle.

03:34.880 --> 03:40.080
As the crust bounces back, melted and flowing crust forms a temporary mountain,

03:40.080 --> 03:45.120
stretching 10 kilometers into the sky. An incredible amount of material is

03:45.120 --> 03:50.560
blasted into the higher atmosphere, or even out into space, as much as 60 times

03:50.560 --> 03:55.280
the original mass of the asteroid. The violence of the strike is felt

03:55.280 --> 04:00.480
everywhere on Earth within minutes. A magnitude 11 earthquake may be the

04:00.480 --> 04:04.960
most powerful quake any living thing has ever witnessed in billions of years.

04:05.520 --> 04:12.160
It is so insanely strong that in India it might have shaken gigantic lava fields and causes

04:12.160 --> 04:18.000
volcanic eruptions that would last for 30,000 years and cover half of the Indian subcontinent

04:18.000 --> 04:24.160
with lava. Even on the side of Earth opposite the impact, the ground still moved by several meters.

04:24.960 --> 04:30.960
Nobody would sleep through this day. The gigantic explosion crashes against the

04:30.960 --> 04:36.800
atmosphere with unprecedented violence and causes a shockwave that reaches speeds of more than 1,000

04:36.800 --> 04:41.760
kilometers per hour near the site of impact, similar to the hyper hurricanes on gas giants

04:41.760 --> 04:48.720
like Neptune. In middle America, basically any soil, vegetation, or animal is just shredded

04:48.720 --> 04:54.480
into pieces and catapulted thousands of kilometers away. Now the previously displaced

04:54.480 --> 05:00.000
oceans return. As the temporary mountain at the site of impact collapses, a ring of tsunamis as

05:00.000 --> 05:04.720
high as one kilometer, enough to cover all skyscrapers humans would ever build, heads in

05:04.720 --> 05:10.000
all directions. As they crash into the coasts of the continents surrounding the impact, they will

05:10.000 --> 05:16.080
drown thousands of kilometers of coastline. 15 hours later, some of the waves that get

05:16.080 --> 05:21.360
refracted around South America will still tower as much as 100 meters into the sky.

05:22.000 --> 05:27.600
But we still haven't talked about the worst thing yet. A lot of the debris yeeted into space will

05:27.600 --> 05:34.320
orbit Earth for thousands of years. Some may hit the moon or even Mars. But most of it comes right

